{"id":"2107.07120","submitter":"Sergey Gusev","authors":"Sergey V. Gusev, Yu Xian Li and Wen Ting Zhang","title":"Limit varieties of monoids satisfying a certain identity","comments":"45 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A limit variety is a variety that is minimal with respect to being\nnon-finitely based. Since the turn of the millennium, much attention has been\ngiven to the classification of limit varieties of aperiodic monoids. Seven\nexplicit examples have so far been found, and the task of locating other\nexamples has recently been reduced to two subproblems, one of which is\nconcerned with monoids that satisfy the identity $xsxt \\approx xsxtx$. In the\npresent article, we provide a complete solution to this subproblem by showing\nthat there are precisely two limit varieties that satisfy this identity. One of\nthem turns out to be the first example having infinitely many subvarieties.\n  It is also deduced that the variety generated by any monoid of order five or\nless contains at most countably many subvarieties.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Jul 2021 04:59:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 14 Mar 2022 16:14:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-15"}
